>The frigid winter water of the river stole the breath right out of Fenri’s lungs as she plunged into the river... to bring more water into her body.

Keep writing. You have something promising here.

There's not a whole lot there so I can't give too much feedback but I will give a couple of suggestions. When it comes to atmosphere you have a great setting to play up but I don't see much of it in the writing. For example, you say they're sitting in a cozy bar. What makes it cozy? Is it small? Is the lighting dim? Orange? Flickering? Where are the protags seated in the bar? Huddled in a dark corner or sitting in the open? Is anyone else in the bar and if so what do they look like? Normal or mysterious? Do any of them react to the conversation between the protags? I don't mean to imply you need to specify every detail of the environment to the viewer but just a few details here and there help get the vibe of the place across to the reader.

Your dialogue is good, but I would warn against the use of ellipses so much. I'm writing a couple stories myself and it's easy to use them as a crutch to make dialogue seem more dramatic. A different way to do the same thing is to split the dialogue into two parts and give an action in between. For example

"I just," Vivi lets out a deep sigh, her shoulders sagging and expression turning despondent. "I need help. A lot of help. From what I've skimmed, most of em' are a two-person job, and well-- *scoff* I'm one."

Most of these posts make reasonable points for consideration. Spend some google search time on what a crematorium has to do to reduce a corpse to ash for a legit funeral. It's a lot of energy ... but what a crematorium does is incredibly thorough & regulated.

Compare to a news story I read some years back. A guy killed someone (adult, forget the relationship) and ashed the corpse using a grill he had set up on the balcony of his apartment. He took the body apart and burned it piece by piece, using store bought charcoal combined with seasoned firewood. He used something like a half a chord of firewood, and took something like 3 days (I'm estimating the details from memory, but I feel sure they're close).

The neighbors complained to the apartment management about the smell & black smoke, but management ignored it until after the guy had successfully finished the job. It was several days after he was done that the police stopped by looking for a missing person, and someone noticed a complaint from the neighbors with the police and added shit up. All that was left was charred bone fragments and teeth. With that as probable cause, they found other blood & DNA traces in the apartment & eventually cracked the case (including purchase of firewood delivery).

Take the "mistakes" into consideration, you can incinerate a corpse to ash using a portable grill, a few bags of charcoal, and half a chord of firewood. I also assume a few quarts of lighter fluid. That will give you a ballpark of the energy requirements to get the job done, and a relative time-frame for doing it in a small fire, as opposed to something a bit larger.

I imagine, if you had a full chord of firewood and chopped the corpse into pieces, you could probably accomplish full incineration in about a 12-hour night of dedicated effort feeding the fire and stirring everything to evenly burn. That would be a large campfire, not an actual bonfire.
